Europe
---
[2] UK
Date: Thu 7 Sep 2017
Source: Penarth Times [edited]
http://www.penarthtimes.co.uk/news/15520779.Measles_warning_is_issued_in_health_board_area/


More than 7600 children between the ages of 5 and 16 in the Cardiff and Vale University Health Board area have not received 2 doses of MMR vaccine and are at risk from measles, according to Public Health Wales.

The warning comes as a measles outbreak affecting the Newport and Torfaen area continues, with 17 confirmed cases of the infection.

The outbreak can be directly linked to an ongoing outbreak of measles in Europe which has seen more than 14 000 cases and dozens of deaths since the beginning of the year [2017].

Although there are no confirmed measles cases in Cardiff and Vale University Health Board at present, Public Health Wales is warning that while the 95 percent vaccination target has not been reached, cases and outbreaks of this potentially deadly infection could be seen anywhere in Wales.

The symptoms of measles include a high temperature, cough, runny nose, red eyes and a distinctive red rash. ...

Parents whose children are not up to date with 2 doses of MMR should ensure that they contact their GP practice to arrange this quick, safe and effective vaccine.

Adults born since 1970, who have never had measles or the MMR vaccine, are also urged to ensure they contact their surgery about vaccination, especially if they work with children.

The 1st dose of MMR is usually given to babies at between 12 and 13 months of age, and the 2nd at 3 years and 4 months of age, but it is never too late to catch up on missed doses.

About one in 5 children with measles can experience serious complications such as ear infections, pneumonia or meningitis. One in 10 children with measles ends up in hospital and in rare cases it can be fatal.

Further information is available at <publichealthwales.org/measles>.

[Byline: Anthony Lewis]

--
