[3] Bulgaria
Date: Thu 7 Sep 2017
Source: Eurosurveillance 22 (36) [edited]
http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ViewArticle.aspx?ArticleId=22873


A Kurchatova et al. 2017. Preliminary Findings Indicate Nosocomial Transmission And Roma Population As Most Affected Group In Ongoing Measles B3 Genotype Outbreak In Bulgaria, March To August 2017. Eurosurveillance 22 (36). Rapid communication

Abstract. From March to August 2017, 165 measles cases were reported from 3 regions in Bulgaria. The age range was 0-55 years and 66 percent of the cases were under 9 years. The Roma population was disproportionally affected (89 percent of cases), 41 percent cases were unvaccinated and in 24 cases there was nosocomial transmission mostly in paediatric departments. A child under 12 months of age died. Control measures have been taken and the investigation is still ongoing.

Discussion. Following the occurrence of the index case in March 2017, 3 clusters of measles cases were registered in Bulgaria. Roma population living in 2 neighbouring regions in Plovdiv and Pazardjik was the most affected group.

According to the latest national census in Bulgaria in 2011 [7], the population consists of Bulgarians (84.8 percent), Turks (8.8 percent) and Roma (4.9 percent). Roma inhabit all regions of the country. They live in overcrowded communities often under poor sanitary conditions and they are characterised by frequent travel within the country and abroad [8].

Up to 2 main features of the ongoing outbreak can be outlined: (i) the existence of a vulnerable group of Roma population non-immunised or insufficiently immunised and (ii) nosocomial measles transmission in the paediatric departments of 2 hospitals in Plovdiv. The recommendation to hospitalise vulnerable Roma children, may also have contributed to the latter. ...-more

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[See full report for references, tables, figures. Measles outbreaks affecting vulnerable groups, including Roma communities, have been reported in other European countries this year. This is a consequence of gaps in vaccine coverage, as has been the unfortunate situation world-wide. - Mod.LK]

