South America
---
[4] Venezuela
Date: Mon 4 Sep 2017 01:15 AM
Source: El Nacional, Venezuela [trans. by LK; edited by Jaime Torres and LK]
http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/sociedad/volvio-sarampion-ocho-meses-despues-que-ops-declarara-pais-libre_202439


For 3 weeks, Bolivar state has [experienced a resurgence of] a disease classified as controlled. Unofficially, 3 cases of measles were confirmed in children hospitalized more than 7 days ago at the Raul Leoni Hospital in Guaiparo, the same health center that had to deal with the wave of diphtheria-affected children since September last year [2016].

At the Vista al Sol outpatient clinic in Ciudad Guayana, 2 cases with clinical diagnosis were referred to the Hospital de Guaiparo 2 weeks ago. Doctors expect results from another 15 samples that were sent to the National Institute of Hygiene because they are suspected by the symptoms presented by the patients.

In September 2016, the Pan American Health Organization announced at the 55th Directing Council that the region had eliminated endemic transmission of measles. Measles was the 5th disease eliminated from the Americas after smallpox (1971), polio (1994) and rubella and congenital rubella syndrome (2015).

In December, PAHO delivered the country's measles-free certificate to Venezuela, which was only valid for 8 months. Last [Sun 3 Sep 2017], PAHO officials were in Guaiparo hospital and were collecting samples.

The El Pais de Uruguay media outlet published on [Tue 5 Sep 2017]: "The outbreak of measles in the state of Bolivar in Venezuela, which affected children aged 5 months and 4 and 9 years, activated a protocol of the Ministry of Public Health that urges people not to stop vaccinating children before a possible contagion with people who are incubating the disease and travel to Uruguay. "

The reappearance of the virus again reveals the low immunization coverage in the country. The Network Defend Epidemiology reported that the last 2 outbreaks occurred in 2002 and 2006--2007, with autochthonous cases, which occurred after the introduction of imported cases, at times of low immunization coverage. In 2012 there were only imported cases.

"Since 2008, immunization coverage (a single dose) has been suboptimal, ranging from 78 percent - 92 percent coverage. The coverage with 2 doses (the 2nd, applied at 5 years), has been frankly insufficient, with a tendency to improve from 2009 onwards. An estimated one million children who have not received the measles vaccine in the last 8 years, "estimates the Network.

[Byline: Isayen Herrera]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Venezuela is in the middle of a political and economic crisis, with severe shortages of food and medicine, as well as lack of medical care. Guyana has decided to intensify measles surveillance near the border with Venezuela, even as nationals of that neighbouring country continue to seek medical treatment [in Guyana] for malaria, government announced [Thu 7 Sep 2017]. Minister of State, Joseph Harmon said the Pan American Health Organisation has advised of increased cases of measles in Bolivar State, Venezuela. As a result, he said Guyana has decided to step up measles surveillance and "adopt a high level of vaccination." (https://demerarawaves.com/2017/09/07/guyana-heightens-measles-surveillance-near-venezuela-border-treating-venezuelans-for-malaria/)
This is a humanitarian move on Guyana's part. - Mod.LK]

[A HealthMap/ProMED map of Venezuela can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5304434,29]

